06062nam a22007095i 9780231538398DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014015955  a(OCoLC)1013945684  a97802315383987 a10.7312/bail167982doi  a(DE-B1597)458235  a(OCoLC)984642287  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aB945.R284bR39 2015 7aPHI0190002bisacsh00aRawls and Religion /ced. by Valentina Gentile, Tom Bailey.  aPilot project. eBook available to selected US libraries only 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. REINTERPRETING RAWLS ON RELIGION -- t1. Respect and War: Against the Standard View of Religion in Politics -- t2. Religion and Liberalism: Was Rawls Right After All? -- t3. Inclusivism, Stability, and Assurance -- t4. Rethinking the Public Use of Religious Reasons -- tPART II. ACCOMMODATING RELIGIONS WITH RAWLS -- t5. The Liberal State and the Religious Citizen: Justificatory Perspectives in Political Liberalism -- t6. Reasoning from Conjecture: A Reply to Three Objections -- t7. The Religious Hermeneutics of Public Reasoning: From Paul to Rawls -- tPART III. TRANSCENDING RAWLS -- t8. E Pluribus Unum: Justification and Redemption in Rawls, Cohen, and Habermas -- t9. A Reasonable Faith? Pope Benedict’s Response to Rawls -- t10. Islamic Politics and the Neutral State: A Friendly Amendment to Rawls? -- tBibliography -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJohn Rawls's influential theory of justice and public reason has often been thought to exclude religion from politics, out of fear of its illiberal and destabilizing potentials. It has therefore been criticized by defenders of religion for marginalizing and alienating the wealth of religious sensibilities, voices, and demands now present in contemporary liberal societies.In this anthology, established scholars of Rawls and the philosophy of religion reexamine and rearticulate the central tenets of Rawls's theory to show they in fact offer sophisticated resources for accommodating and responding to religions in liberal political life. The chapters reassert the subtlety, openness, and flexibility of his sense of liberal "respect" and "consensus," revealing their inclusive implications for religious citizens. They also explore the means he proposes for accommodating nonliberal religions in liberal politics, developing his conception of "public reason" into a novel account of the possibilities for rational engagement between liberal and religious ideas. And they reevaluate Rawls's liberalism from the "transcendent" perspectives of religions themselves, critically considering its normative and political value, as well as its own "religious" character. Rawls and Religion makes a unique and important contribution to contemporary debates over liberalism and its response to the proliferation of religions in contemporary political life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aReligion. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aAn-Na‘im, Abdullahi A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBailey, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBailey, Tom, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEberle, Christopher J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGentile, Valentina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGentile, Valentina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 